Looking at the source code for TemperatureDependentHardeningStressUpdate, it seems that if you have hardening functions at temperatures of 100, 200, 300, 400, and a node is at a temperature of 500, the lines:
  else if (temp <= _hf_temperatures[0])
  {
    _hf_index_lo = 0;
    _hf_index_hi = _hf_index_lo;
    _hf_fraction = 0.0;
  }
  else if (temp >= _hf_temperatures.back())
  {
    _hf_index_lo = _hf_temperatures.size() - 1;
    _hf_index_hi = _hf_index_lo;
    _hf_fraction = 1.0;
  }

indicate that the node will use the hardening function defined for 400 k. However, when I run two models, one with functions at 100, 200, 300, 400, and one with functions at 100, 200, 300, 400, 600 but the 600 function is the same stress-strain function as the one defined at 400, the results are very different. This to me indicates something is going wrong with the handling of these out of range temperature values?
